{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"981f30cb-d481-45c5-a828-0cac27736894","content":"This is a known breaking change. In .NET 10, Android 15 (API 35) enforces **edge-to-edge** rendering, so `AdjustResize` no longer physically shrinks your window. Instead, the OS sends **IME insets** that your layout must react to.\n\nHere are your options, from simplest to most flexible:\n\n### Option 1 — Let MAUI auto-scroll (often sufficient)\n\nMAUI's `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll` is **on by default**. If your input is inside a `ScrollView`, the framework will scroll the focused `Entry`/`Editor` into view automatically. Make sure you haven't disabled it:\n\n```xml\n<!-- Don't do this unless you have a reason -->\n<!-- <Entry KeyboardAutoManagerScroll=\"false\" /> -->\n```\n\nFor a chat screen this alone may not give the right UX, because you want the **whole bottom bar to shift up**, not just scroll to the entry.\n\n### Option 2 — React to keyboard insets (recommended for chat)\n\nAdd bottom padding equal to the keyboard height using platform-specific code:\n\n**Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs**\n```csharp\nusing Android.App;\nusing Android.OS;\nusing Android.Views;\nusing AndroidX.Core.View;\nusing Microsoft.Maui;\n\n[Activity(Theme = \"@style/Maui.SplashTheme\", MainLauncher = true,\n          ConfigurationChanges = /* ...existing flags... */)]\npublic class MainActivity : MauiAppCompatActivity\n{\n    protected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)\n    {\n        base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);\n\n        if (Window?.DecorView is { } decorView)\n        {\n            ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(decorView, new KeyboardInsetsListener());\n        }\n    }\n\n    private class KeyboardInsetsListener : Java.Lang.Object, IOnApplyWindowInsetsListener\n    {\n        public WindowInsetsCompat OnApplyWindowInsets(View view, WindowInsetsCompat insets)\n        {\n            var imeInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime());\n            var navInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.NavigationBars());\n\n            // Use keyboard height when visible, otherwise nav-bar height\n            int bottom = Math.Max(imeInsets.Bottom, navInsets.Bottom);\n\n            view.SetPadding(\n                view.PaddingLeft,\n                view.PaddingTop,\n                view.PaddingRight,\n                bottom);\n\n            return insets;\n        }\n    }\n}\n```\n\nThis makes Android push your entire MAUI layout up by exactly the keyboard height—no XAML changes needed.\n\n### Option 3 — Quick-and-dirty fallback\n\nIf you just need something working fast, switch to `AdjustPan` in `AndroidManifest.xml`:\n\n```xml\n<activity android:windowSoftInputMode=\"adjustPan\" ... />\n```\n\nThis pans the whole window up so the focused field is visible, but it **hides content at the top** and you lose fine-grained control.\n\n---\n\n**TL;DR:** For a chat screen, **Option 2** is the way to go—it replaces what `AdjustResize` used to do, but via the modern insets API that edge-to-edge requires.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3b63fffd-da9b-4f12-a634-2b1a6ebac68b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET MAUI issue where the keyboard covers the text input at the bottom of the screen. They mention that `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` worked in .NET 9 but doesn't work in .NET 10. This is a known change in .NET MAUI / Android behavior.\n\nLet me provide a concise answer based on my knowledge:\n\nIn .NET 10 (and actually starting with .NET 9 in some previews), the Android platform moved to edge-to-edge rendering by default, which changes how `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` works. \n\nThe `Resize` mode was deprecated in Android API 30+, and since .NET 10 targets API 35+ by default with edge-to-edge enabled, the old approach no longer works as expected. The recommended solution is to use the `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll` behavior that was introduced in .NET MAUI, which properly handles keyboard insets in the new edge-to-edge environment. in the keyboard insets. The practical solution for .NET 10 is to ensure `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll` isn't disabled and use padding that responds to keyboard insets, since `AdjustResize` no longer works as it did before on modern Android with edge-to-edge layouts.\n\nWriting platform-specific code... Setting up the window insets listener... I'm realizing the cleaner approach for .NET 10 MAUI is to rely on the built-in `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll` behavior rather than trying to manually handle window insets, and structure the chat layout with a `ScrollView` or `Grid` so the auto-scroll can work properly—platform-specific inset handling can be added if needed for edge cases.","outputTokens":2451,"requestId":"B7D0:2A1B2F:18E303:205330:69FFDA8E"},"id":"c23d186a-521f-46df-b95f-19c5682c4bfe","timestamp":"2026-05-10T01:09:20.985Z","parentId":"6527d7e1-0e9d-43ad-a122-fb4b2bec4794"}
